body:
It's not that weird of a decision once you look at the code that depends on it.

Essentially, if I code something like:
```c++
for (auto& it : mapTx) {
    auto it2 = FindIterByPrevout(it->GetTransaction()->vin[0].prevout);
    if (visited(it2)) continue;
}
```

this is kind of semantic, because if the FindByPrevout returns nullopt then we want to skip it because we've (in theory) already traversed everything we could want to traverse.


@sdaftuar and I spent like at least an hour trying to come up with a better semantic name than the predecessor to visited, and decided that visited was sufficiently semantic. But if you have a better suggestion, would be happy to consider it, we just couldn't come up with something that wasn't either awkward sounding or less semantic in other cases.

Ah I think here's the miscommunication of what the algorithm "GetComponents" does. It's something like:

```c++
vector<vector<txiter>> components;
for (auto elt: mapTx) {
   vector<txiter> to_process;
   vector<txiter> processed;
   if (visited(elt)) continue;
   to_process.push_back(elt);
   while (to_process.size()) {
    auto todo = to_process.back();
    to_process.pop_back();
    processed.push_back(todo);
   for(auto y : GetMemPoolChildren(todo)) {
        if (visited(y)) continue;
        to_process.push_back(y);
   }
   for(auto x : GetMemPoolParents(todo)) {
       if (visited(x)) continue;
        to_process.push_back(x);
    }

}
    component.push_back(processed);
}
```

This lets you find all connected components I think, and passes the test of B-first. A is a parent of B, so then A goes into the to_process stack, then C is a child of A, so C goes onto the to_process stack.

Without epochs this would be much messier, but with epochs we can see that things only go onto the stack one time ever because of the visited guards.
